The two points $(-2, 4)$ and $(8, 4)$ lie on a horizontal line, so the major axis of the ellipse is horizontal.  The center of the ellipse is the midpoint of the segment connecting these two points, which is $(3, 4).$

[asy]
unitsize (0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, F1, F2, O;

A = (-2,4);
B = (8,4);
C = (3,-2);
O = (3,4);
F1 = (3 - sqrt(35),4);
F2 = (3 + sqrt(35),4);

draw((-3,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,-3)--(0,6));
draw(Circle(O,sqrt(35)),linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--B);
draw(O--C);
draw(O--F1);
draw(O--F2);

dot("$(-2,4)$", A, SW);
dot("$(8,4)$", B, SE);
dot("$(3,-2)$", C, S);
dot("$(3,4)$", O, NE);
dot("$F_1$", F1, S);
dot("$F_2$", F2, S);
[/asy]

The distance between the center of the ellipse and the point $(3, -2)$ is 6.  This is the minor radius of the ellipse, so $b = 6.$

The distance between the center of the ellipse and the point $(-2, 4)$ is 5.  This is the semi-major axis of the ellipse, so $a = 5.$

The distance between the foci is $2c,$ where $c^2 = a^2 - b^2 = 25 - 36 = -11.$  Thus, $c = \sqrt{11} i,$ so $2c = \boxed{2 \sqrt{11}}.$

